title: Determination of differential elastic and inelastic and double-differential neutron scattering cross sections of Nb-93 at energies between 7.10 MeV and 14.10 MeV.

x4freetext: sections of Nb-93 at energies between 7.10 MeV and
pulse width 1 nanosec, and multi-angle neutron
Deuterium gas target, 1.0 cm in diameter and
3.0 cm in length, gas pressure 1.9-2.0 kPa.
Mean neutron energy is defined within +/- 20 keV.
n/gamma discrimination with pulse shape analysis.
behind a massive collimator shielding in a distance
of 1200 cm from the sample. The angle separation
between the detectors is 12.5 deg. The angle region
covered is from 12.5 deg to 160 deg.
.An additional NE213 detector was used as relative
fluence monitor, diameter 3.81 cm, length 3.81 cm.
The movable monitor (in a fixed distance of 651 cm)
was always in a position of 58.9 deg relative
diameter 25.0 mm, height 49.6 mm, mass 208.88 g,
placed 17.5 cm from the gas target centre.
.Inelastic cross sections were extracted based on the
assumption of an isotopic abundance of Nb-93 of 100%.
The elastic cross sections include the inelastic
Partial inelastic cross sections were determined
for level groups with a mean excitation energy
of 0.95 MeV and 1.54 MeV, respectively, and for
the 2.15 MeV level. The inelastic scattering for
higher-lying levels was treated as DDX.
.Monte Carlo simulated TOF spectra of the complete
angular distribution were iteratively adjusted to
the measured TOF spectra. The simulation comprised
the neutron production in the gas target and the
scattering geometry between target, sample and
.For parasitic neutrons from the D(d,np) breakup
reaction were simulated and subtracted. The data for
the simulation were adjusted by additional measure-
ments of the neutron scattering with a 4-He(d,np)
Total errors comprise counting statistics and

.An additional uncertainty of 5% of the ratio N-bu/N-in
